[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] In mathematics, the **binomial coefficients** are the positive integers that occur as coefficients in the binomial theorem.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Commonly, a binomial coefficient is indexed by a pair of integers *n* ≥ *k* ≥ 0 and is written ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ or ⁠ $C(n,k)$ ⁠.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The binomial coefficients occur in many areas of mathematics, and especially in combinatorics.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] In combinatorics the symbol ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ is usually read as "n choose k" because there are ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ ways to choose an (unordered) subset of k elements from a fixed set of n elements.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The binomial coefficients can be extended to accept more general families of inputs.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] When n is a nonnegative integer and k is an integer such that *k* < 0 or *k* > *n*, it is common to define ⁠ ${\tbinom {n}{k}}=0$ ⁠.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] If k is a nonnegative integer and z is any complex number, the first multiplicative formula above can be used to define ⁠ ${\tbinom {z}{k}}$ ⁠.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Many of the properties of binomial coefficients continue to hold in these more general contexts.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Andreas von Ettingshausen introduced the notation ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ in 1826, although the numbers were known centuries earlier (see Pascal's triangle).
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Around 1150, the Indian mathematician Bhaskaracharya gave an exposition of binomial coefficients in his book *Līlāvatī*.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Alternative notations include *C*(*n*, *k*), *n**C**k*, *n**C**k*, *C**k* *n*, *C**n* *k*, and *C**n*,*k*, in all of which the C stands for *combinations* or *choices*; the C notation means the number of ways to choose *k* out of *n* objects.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Many calculators use variants of the C notation because they can represent it on a single-line display.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] In this form the binomial coefficients are easily compared to the numbers of k-permutations of n, written as *P*(*n*, *k*), etc.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] For natural numbers (taken to include 0) n and k, the binomial coefficient ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ can be defined as the coefficient of the monomial *X**k* in the expansion of (1 + *X*)*n*.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] (valid for any elements x, y of a commutative ring), which explains the name "binomial coefficient".
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Another occurrence of this number is in combinatorics, where it gives the number of ways, disregarding order, that k objects can be chosen from among n objects; more formally, the number of k-element subsets (or k-combinations) of an n-element set.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] This shows in particular that ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ is a natural number for any natural numbers n and k.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Most of these interpretations can be shown to be equivalent to counting k-combinations.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Several methods exist to compute the value of ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ without actually expanding a binomial power or counting k-combinations.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] One method uses the recursive, purely additive formula ${\binom {n}{k}}={\binom {n-1}{k-1}}+{\binom {n-1}{k}}$ for all integers $n,k$ such that ⁠ $1\leq k<n$ ⁠, with boundary values ${\binom {n}{0}}={\binom {n}{n}}=1$ for all integers *n* ≥ 0.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] It also follows from tracing the contributions to *X**k* in (1 + *X*)*n*−1(1 + *X*).
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] As there is zero *X**n*+1 or *X*−1 in (1 + *X*)*n*, one might extend the definition beyond the above boundaries to include ${\tbinom {n}{k}}=0$ when either *k* > *n* or *k* < 0.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] This recursive formula then allows the construction of Pascal's triangle, surrounded by white spaces where the zeros, or the trivial coefficients, would be.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] This formula is easiest to understand for the combinatorial interpretation of binomial coefficients.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The numerator gives the number of ways to select a sequence of k distinct objects, retaining the order of selection, from a set of n objects.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The denominator counts the number of distinct sequences that define the same k-combination when order is disregarded.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] This formula can also be stated in a recursive form.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] It is readily derived by evaluating $C_{n,k}/C_{n,k-1}$ and can intuitively be understood as starting at the leftmost coefficient of the ⁠ n ⁠-th row of Pascal's triangle, whose value is always ⁠ 1 ⁠, and recursively computing the next coefficient to its right until the ⁠ k ⁠-th one is reached.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Due to the symmetry of the binomial coefficients with regard to k and *n* − *k*, calculation of the above product, as well as the recursive relation, may be optimised by setting its upper limit to the smaller of k and *n* − *k*.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Finally, there is the compact form, often used in proofs and derivations, which makes repeated use of the familiar factorial function: ${\binom {n}{k}}={\frac {n!}{k!\,(n-k)!}}\quad {\text{for }}\ 0\leq k\leq n,$ where *n*! denotes the factorial of n.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] This formula follows from the multiplicative formula above by multiplying numerator and denominator by (*n* − *k*)!; as a consequence it involves many factors common to numerator and denominator.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] It is less practical for explicit computation (in the case that k is small and n is large) unless common factors are first cancelled (in particular since factorial values grow very rapidly).
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] which leads to a more efficient multiplicative computational routine.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] This formula is valid for all complex numbers *α* and *X* with |*X*| < 1.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] If *α* is a nonnegative integer *n*, then all terms with *k* > *n* are zero, and the infinite series becomes a finite sum, thereby recovering the binomial formula.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] However, for other values of *α*, including negative integers and rational numbers, the series is really infinite.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] which can be used to prove by mathematical induction that ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ is a natural number for all integer *n* ≥ 0 and all integer *k*, a fact that is not immediately obvious from formula (1).
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] To the left and right of Pascal's triangle, the entries (shown as blanks) are all zero.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Row number n contains the numbers ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ for *k* = 0, …, *n*.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] It is constructed by first placing 1s in the outermost positions, and then filling each inner position with the sum of the two numbers directly above.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] This method allows the quick calculation of binomial coefficients without the need for fractions or multiplications.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] As such, it can be evaluated at any real or complex number *t* to define binomial coefficients with such first arguments.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] These "generalized binomial coefficients" appear in Newton's generalized binomial theorem.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Each polynomial ${\tbinom {t}{k}}$ is integer-valued: it has an integer value at all integer inputs ⁠ t ⁠.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] (One way to prove this is by induction on *k* using Pascal's identity.) Therefore, any integer linear combination of binomial coefficient polynomials is integer-valued too.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Conversely, (**4**) shows that any integer-valued polynomial is an integer linear combination of these binomial coefficient polynomials.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] More generally, for any subring *R* of a characteristic 0 field *K*, a polynomial in *K*[*t*] takes values in *R* at all integers if and only if it is an *R*-linear combination of binomial coefficient polynomials.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The factorial formula facilitates relating nearby binomial coefficients.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] says that the elements in the nth row of Pascal's triangle always add up to 2 raised to the nth power.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] This is obtained from the binomial theorem (**∗**) by setting *x* = 1 and *y* = 1.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The formula also has a natural combinatorial interpretation: the left side sums the number of subsets of {1, ..., *n*} of sizes *k* = 0, 1, ..., *n*, giving the total number of subsets.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] (That is, the left side counts the power set of {1, ..., *n*}.) However, these subsets can also be generated by successively choosing or excluding each element 1, ..., *n*; the *n* independent binary choices (bit-strings) allow a total of $2^{n}$ choices.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The left and right sides are two ways to count the same collection of subsets, so they are equal.
