[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] This formula is used in the analysis of the German tank problem.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Many identities involving binomial coefficients can be proved by combinatorial means.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] For example, for nonnegative integers ⁠ ${n}\geq {q}$ ⁠, the identity $\sum _{k=q}^{n}{\binom {n}{k}}{\binom {k}{q}}=2^{n-q}{\binom {n}{q}}$ (which reduces to (**6**) when *q* = 1) can be given a double counting proof, as follows.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The left side counts the number of ways of selecting a subset of [*n*] = {1, 2, ..., *n*} with at least *q* elements, and marking *q* elements among those selected.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The right side counts the same thing, because there are ${\tbinom {n}{q}}$ ways of choosing a set of *q* elements to mark, and $2^{n-q}$ to choose which of the remaining elements of [*n*] also belong to the subset.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] In Pascal's identity ${\binom {n}{k}}={\binom {n-1}{k-1}}+{\binom {n-1}{k}},$ both sides count the number of *k*-element subsets of [*n*]: the two terms on the right side group them into those that contain element *n* and those that do not.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The identity (**8**) also has a combinatorial proof.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Suppose you have $2n$ empty squares arranged in a row and you want to mark (select) *n* of them.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] There are ${\tbinom {2n}{n}}$ ways to do this.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] On the other hand, you may select your *n* squares by selecting *k* squares from among the first *n* and $n-k$ squares from the remaining *n* squares; any *k* from 0 to *n* will work.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] If one denotes by *F*(*i*) the sequence of Fibonacci numbers, indexed so that *F*(0) = *F*(1) = 1, then the identity $\sum _{k=0}^{\left\lfloor {\frac {n}{2}}\right\rfloor }{\binom {n-k}{k}}=F(n)$ has the following combinatorial proof.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] One may show by induction that *F*(*n*) counts the number of ways that a *n* × 1 strip of squares may be covered by 2 × 1 and 1 × 1 tiles.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] On the other hand, if such a tiling uses exactly k of the 2 × 1 tiles, then it uses *n* − 2*k* of the 1 × 1 tiles, and so uses *n* − *k* tiles total.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] There are ${\tbinom {n-k}{k}}$ ways to order these tiles, and so summing this coefficient over all possible values of k gives the identity.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The number of *k*-combinations for all *k*, ⁠ $\sum _{0\leq {k}\leq {n}}{\binom {n}{k}}=2^{n}$ ⁠, is the sum of the *n*th row (counting from 0) of the binomial coefficients.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] These combinations are enumerated by the 1 digits of the set of base 2 numbers counting from 0 to ⁠ $2^{n}-1$ ⁠, where each digit position is an item from the set of *n*.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] These can be proved by using Euler's formula to convert trigonometric functions to complex exponentials, expanding using the binomial theorem, and integrating term by term.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] More generally, this remains true if *n* is any number and *k* is such that all the numbers between 1 and *k* are coprime to *n*.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] A symmetric bivariate generating function of the binomial coefficients is $\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }\sum _{k=0}^{\infty }{\binom {n+k}{k}}x^{k}y^{n}={\frac {1}{1-x-y}}.$ which is the same as the previous generating function after the substitution ⁠ $x\to xy$ ⁠.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] In 1852, Kummer proved that if *m* and *n* are nonnegative integers and *p* is a prime number, then the largest power of *p* dividing ${\tbinom {m+n}{m}}$ equals *p**c*, where *c* is the number of carries when *m* and *n* are added in base *p*.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Equivalently, the exponent of a prime *p* in ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ equals the number of nonnegative integers *j* such that the fractional part of *k*/*p**j* is greater than the fractional part of *n*/*p**j*.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] (For example, ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ is not divisible by *p* if every digit in the base-*p* representation of *k* is less than or equal to the corresponding digit in the base-*p* representation of *n*.) It can be deduced from this that ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ is divisible by *n*/gcd(*n*,*k*).
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] In particular therefore it follows that *p* divides ${\tbinom {p^{r}}{s}}$ for all positive integers *r* and *s* such that *s* < *p**r*.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] However this is not true of higher powers of *p*: for example 9 does not divide ⁠ ${\tbinom {9}{6}}$ ⁠.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Any integer divides almost all binomial coefficients.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] More precisely, fix an integer *d* and let *f*(*N*) denote the number of binomial coefficients ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ with $n<N$ such that *d* divides ⁠ ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ ⁠.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Then $\lim _{N\to \infty }{\frac {f(N)}{N(N+1)/2}}=1.$ Since the number of binomial coefficients ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ with *n* < *N* is *N*(*N* + 1) / 2, this implies that the density of binomial coefficients divisible by *d* goes to 1.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Binomial coefficients have divisibility properties related to least common multiples of consecutive integers.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Another fact: An integer *n* ≥ 2 is prime if and only if all the intermediate binomial coefficients ${\binom {n}{1}},{\binom {n}{2}},\ldots ,{\binom {n}{n-1}}$ are divisible by *n*.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Proof: When *p* is prime, *p* divides ${\binom {p}{k}}={\frac {p\cdot (p-1)\cdots (p-k+1)}{k\cdot (k-1)\cdots 1}}$ for all 0 < *k* < *p* because ${\tbinom {p}{k}}$ is a natural number and *p* divides the numerator but not the denominator.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] When *n* is composite, let *p* be the smallest prime factor of *n* and let *k* = *n*/*p*.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] But *n* is divisible by *p*, so *p* does not divide *n* − 1, *n* − 2, …, *n* − *p* + 1 and because *p* is prime, we know that *p* does not divide (*n* − 1)(*n* − 2)⋯(*n* − *p* + 1) and so the numerator cannot be divisible by *n*.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] A similar argument can be made to show the second inequality.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The final strict inequality is equivalent to ⁠ $e^{k}>k^{k}/k!$ ⁠, that is clear since the RHS is a term of the exponential series ⁠ $e^{k}=\sum _{j=0}^{\infty }k^{j}/j!$ ⁠.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] From the divisibility properties we can infer that ${\frac {\operatorname {lcm} (n-k,\ldots ,n)}{(n-k)\cdot \operatorname {lcm} \left({\binom {k}{0}},\ldots ,{\binom {k}{k}}\right)}}\leq {\binom {n}{k}}\leq {\frac {\operatorname {lcm} (n-k,\ldots ,n)}{n-k}},$ where both equalities can be achieved.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] If *n* is large and *k* is linear in *n*, various precise asymptotic estimates exist for the binomial coefficient ⁠ ${\binom {n}{k}}$ ⁠.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] This asymptotic behaviour is contained in the approximation ${\binom {z+k}{k}}\approx {\frac {e^{z(H_{k}-\gamma )}}{\Gamma (z+1)}}$ as well.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The combinatorial interpretation of multinomial coefficients is distribution of *n* distinguishable elements over *r* (distinguishable) containers, each containing exactly *ki* elements, where *i* is the index of the container.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The definition of the binomial coefficients can be extended to the case where n is real and k is integer.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] where the connection coefficients are multinomial coefficients.
