[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The identity can be obtained by showing that both sides satisfy the differential equation (1 + *z*) *f'*(*z*) = *α* *f*(*z*).
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The radius of convergence of this series is 1.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Binomial coefficients count subsets of prescribed size from a given set.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] A related combinatorial problem is to count multisets of prescribed size with elements drawn from a given set, that is, to count the number of ways to select a certain number of elements from a given set with the possibility of selecting the same element repeatedly.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The resulting numbers are called *multiset coefficients*; the number of ways to "multichoose" (i.e., choose with replacement) *k* items from an *n* element set is denoted ⁠ $\left(\!\!{\binom {n}{k}}\!\!\right)$ ⁠.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] To avoid ambiguity and confusion with *n'*s main denotation in this article, let *f* = *n* = *r* + (*k* − 1) and *r* = *f* − (*k* − 1).
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The resulting function has been little-studied, apparently first being graphed in (Fowler 1996).
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The binomial coefficient has a *q*-analog generalization known as the Gaussian binomial coefficient.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] The definition of the binomial coefficient can be generalized to infinite cardinals by defining: ${\binom {\alpha }{\beta }}=\left|\left\{B\subseteq A:\left|B\right|=\beta \right\}\right|$ where A is some set with cardinality ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] One can show that the generalized binomial coefficient is well-defined, in the sense that no matter what set we choose to represent the cardinal number ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠, ${\textstyle {\alpha \choose \beta }}$ will remain the same.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] For finite cardinals, this definition coincides with the standard definition of the binomial coefficient.
[src:generating-functions/binomial-coefficient] Assuming the Axiom of Choice, one can show that ${\textstyle {\binom {\alpha }{\alpha }}=2^{\alpha }}$ for any infinite cardinal ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The **Catalan numbers** are a sequence of natural numbers that occur in various counting problems, often involving recursively defined objects.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] They are named after Eugène Catalan, though they were previously discovered in the 1730s by Minggatu.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] This expression shows that *C**n* is an integer, which is not immediately obvious from the first formula given.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] This expression forms the basis for a proof of the correctness of the formula.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Another alternative expression is $C_{n}={\frac {1}{2n+1}}{\binom {2n+1}{n}}\,,$ which can be directly interpreted in terms of the cycle lemma; see below.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Asymptotically, the Catalan numbers grow as $C_{n}\sim {\frac {4^{n}}{n^{\frac {3}{2}}{\sqrt {\pi }}}}\,,$ in the sense that the quotient of the nth Catalan number and the expression on the right tends towards 1 as n approaches infinity.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] This can be proved by using the asymptotic growth of the central binomial coefficients, by Stirling's approximation for *n*!, or via generating functions.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The only Catalan numbers *C**n* that are odd are those for which *n* = 2*k* − 1; all others are even.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The only prime Catalan numbers are *C*2 = 2 and *C*3 = 5.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] More generally, the multiplicity with which a prime p divides *C**n* can be determined by first expressing *n* + 1 in base p.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] For *p* = 2, the multiplicity is the number of 1 bits, minus 1.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] For p an odd prime, count all digits greater than ⁠*p* + 1/2⁠; also count digits equal to ⁠*p* + 1/2⁠ unless final; and count digits equal to ⁠*p* − 1/2⁠ if not final and the next digit is counted.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The odd Catalan numbers, *C**n* for *n* = 2*k* − 1, do not have last digit 5 if *n* + 1 has a base 5 representation containing 0, 1 and 2 only, except in the least significant place, which could also be a 3.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] This has a simple probabilistic interpretation.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Consider a random walk on the integer line, starting at 0.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Let −1 be a "trap" state, such that if the walker arrives at −1, it will remain there.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The walker can arrive at the trap state at times 1, 3, 5, 7,… and the number of ways the walker can arrive at the trap state at time 2*k* + 1 is *C**k*.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] There are many counting problems in combinatorics whose solution is given by the Catalan numbers.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The book *Enumerative Combinatorics: Volume 2* by combinatorialist Richard P.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Stanley contains a set of exercises which describe 66 different interpretations of the Catalan numbers.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Following are some examples, with illustrations of the cases *C*3 = 5 and *C*4 = 14.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] There are several ways of explaining why the formula $C_{n}={\frac {1}{n+1}}{2n \choose n}$ solves the combinatorial problems listed above.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The first proof below uses a generating function.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The other proofs are examples of bijective proofs; they involve literally counting a collection of some kind of object to arrive at the correct formula.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] with (possibly empty) Dyck words *w*1 and *w*2.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] in other words, this equation follows from the recurrence relation by expanding both sides into power series.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Call a bad path one that starts at (*x*, *y*) = (0, 0), ends at (*n*, *n*), is monotonic, and contains a point above the line *y* = *x*.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] We count the number of bad paths by establishing a bijection with paths that start at (0, 0), end at (*n* − 1, *n* + 1), and are monotonic.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] For a given bad path, construct a reflected path as follows.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Let P be the first point on the bad path intersecting the line *y* = *x* + 1.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The bad path from (0, 0) to P is the beginning of the reflected path.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The part of the bad path from P to (*n*, *n*) reflected across the line *y* = *x* + 1 is the rest of the reflected path.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The black line is the points shared between the two paths, the dotted red line is the rest of the bad path, the solid red line is the rest of the reflected path.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] This is a bijection because every monotonic path from (0, 0) to (*n* − 1, *n* + 1) is constructable from a bad path, and every reflected path is uniquely invertible by finding the unique point P, which must exist because every such path must intersect *y* = *x* + 1.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The number of steps in the reflected path is (*n* − 1) + (*n* + 1) = 2*n*.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The number of upward steps is *n* + 1 because the path is monotonic and starts at *y* = 0 and ends at *y* = *n* + 1.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] This proof can be restated in terms of Dyck words.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] We start with a (non-Dyck) sequence of n Xs and n Ys and interchange all Xs and Ys after the first Y that violates the Dyck condition.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] This bijective proof provides a natural explanation for the term *n* + 1 appearing in the denominator of the formula for *C**n*.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] A generalized version of this proof can be found in a paper of Rukavicka (2011).
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Given a monotonic path, the **exceedance** of the path is defined to be the number of **vertical** edges above the diagonal.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] For example, in Figure 2, the edges above the diagonal are marked in red, so the exceedance of this path is 5.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Given a monotonic path whose exceedance is not zero, we apply the following algorithm to construct a new path whose exceedance is 1 less than the one we started with.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] In Figure 3, the black dot indicates the point where the path first crosses the diagonal.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The black edge is X, and we place the last lattice point of the red portion in the top-right corner, and the first lattice point of the green portion in the bottom-left corner, and place X accordingly, to make a new path, shown in the second diagram.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] It can be seen that this process is *reversible*: given any path P whose exceedance is less than n, there is exactly one path which yields P when the algorithm is applied to it.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Indeed, the (black) edge X, which originally was the first horizontal step ending on the diagonal, has become the *last* horizontal step *starting* on the diagonal.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Alternatively, reverse the original algorithm to look for the first edge that passes *below* the diagonal.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] This implies that the number of paths of exceedance n is equal to the number of paths of exceedance *n* − 1, which is equal to the number of paths of exceedance *n* − 2, and so on, down to zero.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] In other words, we have split up the set of *all* monotonic paths into *n* + 1 equally sized classes, corresponding to the possible exceedances between 0 and n.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Figure 4 illustrates the situation for *n* = 3.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Each of the 20 possible monotonic paths appears somewhere in the table.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The first column shows all paths of exceedance three, which lie entirely above the diagonal.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The columns to the right show the result of successive applications of the algorithm, with the exceedance decreasing one unit at a time.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] There are five rows, that is *C*3 = 5, and the last column displays all paths no higher than the diagonal.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Using Dyck words, start with a sequence from ${\textstyle {\binom {2n}{n}}}$ .
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Let *X**d* be the first X that brings an initial subsequence to equality, and configure the sequence as (*F*)*Xd*(*L*).
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] This proof uses the triangulation definition of Catalan numbers to establish a relation between *C**n* and *C**n*+1.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Given a polygon P with *n* + 2 sides and a triangulation, mark one of its sides as the base, and also orient one of its 2*n* + 1 total edges.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] There are (4*n* + 2)*C**n* such marked triangulations for a given base.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Given a polygon Q with *n* + 3 sides and a (different) triangulation, again mark one of its sides as the base.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Mark one of the sides other than the base side (and not an inner triangle edge).
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] There are (*n* + 2)*C**n* + 1 such marked triangulations for a given base.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] There is a simple bijection between these two marked triangulations: We can either collapse the triangle in Q whose side is marked (in two ways, and subtract the two that cannot collapse the base), or, in reverse, expand the oriented edge in P to a triangle and mark its new side.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Applying the recursion with *C*0 = 1 gives the result.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] This proof is based on the Dyck words interpretation of the Catalan numbers, so Cn is the number of ways to correctly match n pairs of brackets.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] We denote a (possibly empty) correct string with c and its inverse with c′.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Since any c can be uniquely decomposed into *c* = (*c*1)*c*2, summing over the possible lengths of *c*1 immediately gives the recursive definition $C_{0}=1\quad {\text{and}}\quad C_{n+1}=\sum _{i=0}^{n}C_{i}\,C_{n-i}\quad {\text{for }}n\geq 0$ .
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Let b be a balanced string of length 2*n*, i.e. b contains an equal number of ( and ), so *Bn* = ${\textstyle {\binom {2n}{n}}}$ .
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] This proof is based on the Dyck words interpretation of the Catalan numbers and uses the cycle lemma of Dvoretzky and Motzkin.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] We call a sequence of Xs and Ys *dominating* if, reading from left to right, the number of Xs is always strictly greater than the number of Ys.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The cycle lemma states that any sequence of m Xs and n Ys, where *m* > *n*, has precisely *m* − *n* dominating circular shifts.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] To see this, arrange the given sequence of *m* + *n* Xs and Ys in a circle.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Repeatedly removing XY pairs leaves exactly *m* − *n* Xs.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Each of these Xs was the start of a dominating circular shift before anything was removed.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] This sequence is dominating, but none of its circular shifts XYXYX, YXYXX, XYXXY and YXXYX are.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] A string is a Dyck word of n Xs and n Ys if and only if prepending an X to the Dyck word gives a dominating sequence with *n* + 1 Xs and n Ys, so we can count the former by instead counting the latter.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] In particular, when *m* = *n* + 1, there is exactly one dominating circular shift.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] There are ${\textstyle {\binom {2n+1}{n}}}$ sequences with exactly *n* + 1 Xs and n Ys.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] For each of these, only one of the 2*n* + 1 circular shifts is dominating.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Therefore there are ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{2n+1}}{\binom {2n+1}{n}}}$ = *Cn* distinct sequences of *n* + 1 Xs and n Ys that are dominating, each of which corresponds to exactly one Dyck word.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The *n* × *n* Hankel matrix whose (*i*, *j*) entry is the Catalan number *C**i*+*j*−2 has determinant 1, regardless of the value of n.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Moreover, if the indexing is "shifted" so that the (*i*, *j*) entry is filled with the Catalan number *C**i*+*j*−1 then the determinant is still 1, regardless of the value of n.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Taken together, these two conditions uniquely define the Catalan numbers.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Another feature unique to the Catalan–Hankel matrix is that the *n* × *n* submatrix starting at 2 has determinant *n* + 1.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The Catalan sequence was described in 1751 by Leonhard Euler, who was interested in the number of different ways of dividing a polygon into triangles.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The sequence is named after Eugène Charles Catalan, who discovered the connection to parenthesized expressions during his exploration of the Towers of Hanoi puzzle.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The reflection counting trick (second proof) for Dyck words was found by Désiré André in 1887.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The name “Catalan numbers” originated from John Riordan.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Larcombe (1999) sketched some of the features of the work of Mingantu, including the stimulus of Pierre Jartoux, who brought three infinite series to China early in the 1700s.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] For instance, Mingantu used the Catalan sequence to express series expansions of $\sin(2\alpha )$ and $\sin(4\alpha )$ in terms of $\sin(\alpha )$ .
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The Catalan numbers can be interpreted as a special case of the Bertrand's ballot theorem.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] Specifically, $C_{n}$ is the number of ways for a candidate A with *n* + 1 votes to lead candidate B with n votes.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The two-parameter sequence of non-negative integers ${\frac {(2m)!(2n)!}{(m+n)!m!n!}}$ is a generalization of the Catalan numbers.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] These are named **super-Catalan numbers**, per Ira Gessel.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] These should not confused with the Schröder–Hipparchus numbers, which sometimes are also called super-Catalan numbers.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] For $m=1$ , this is just two times the ordinary Catalan numbers, and for $m=n$ , the numbers have an easy combinatorial description.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] However, other combinatorial descriptions are only known for $m=2,3$ and 4 , and it is an open problem to find a general combinatorial interpretation.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The classical Catalan number $C_{n}$ corresponds to the root system of type $A_{n}$ .
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The classical recurrence relation generalizes: the Catalan number of a Coxeter diagram is equal to the sum of the Catalan numbers of all its maximal proper sub-diagrams.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] The Catalan numbers are a solution of a version of the Hausdorff moment problem.
[src:generating-functions/catalan-number] For coprime positive integers r and s, the *rational Catalan numbers* ${\frac {1}{r+s}}{\binom {r+s}{r}}$ count the number of lattice paths with steps of unit length rightwards and upwards from (0,0) to (*r*,*s*) that never go above the line *ry* = *sx*.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] In mathematics, a **generating function** is a representation of an infinite sequence of numbers as the coefficients of a formal power series.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Generating functions are often expressed in closed form (rather than as a series), by some expression involving operations on the formal series.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] There are various types of generating functions, including **ordinary generating functions**, **exponential generating functions**, *Lambert series*, *Bell series*, and *Dirichlet series*.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Every sequence in principle has a generating function of each type (except that Lambert and Dirichlet series require indices to start at 1 rather than 0), but the ease with which they can be handled may differ considerably.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] The particular generating function, if any, that is most useful in a given context will depend upon the nature of the sequence and the details of the problem being addressed.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Generating functions are sometimes called **generating series**, in that a series of terms can be said to be the generator of its sequence of term coefficients.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Generating functions were first introduced by Abraham de Moivre in 1730, in order to solve the general linear recurrence problem.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Unlike an ordinary series, the *formal* power series is not required to converge: in fact, the generating function is not actually regarded as a function, and the "variable" remains an indeterminate.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] One can generalize to formal power series in more than one indeterminate, to encode information about infinite multi-dimensional arrays of numbers.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Thus generating functions are not functions in the formal sense of a mapping from a domain to a codomain.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] These expressions in terms of the indeterminate x may involve arithmetic operations, differentiation with respect to x and composition with (i.e., substitution into) other generating functions; since these operations are also defined for functions, the result looks like a function of x.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Indeed, the closed form expression can often be interpreted as a function that can be evaluated at (sufficiently small) concrete values of x, and which has the formal series as its series expansion; this explains the designation "generating functions".
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] However such interpretation is not required to be possible, because formal series are not required to give a convergent series when a nonzero numeric value is substituted for x.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Not all expressions that are meaningful as functions of x are meaningful as expressions designating formal series; for example, negative and fractional powers of x are examples of functions that do not have a corresponding formal power series.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] When the term *generating function* is used without qualification, it is usually taken to mean an ordinary generating function.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] The *ordinary generating function* of a sequence *a**n* is: $G(a_{n};x)=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }a_{n}x^{n}.$ If *a**n* is the probability mass function of a discrete random variable, then its ordinary generating function is called a probability-generating function.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Exponential generating functions are generally more convenient than ordinary generating functions for combinatorial enumeration problems that involve labelled objects.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Another benefit of exponential generating functions is that they are useful in transferring linear recurrence relations to the realm of differential equations.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] For example, take the Fibonacci sequence {*fn*} that satisfies the linear recurrence relation *f**n*+2 = *f**n*+1 + *f**n*.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] and its derivatives can readily be shown to satisfy the differential equation EF″(*x*) = EF′(*x*) + EF(*x*) as a direct analogue with the recurrence relation above.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] In this view, the factorial term *n*! is merely a counter-term to normalise the derivative operator acting on *x**n*.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] The *Lambert series* of a sequence *a**n* is $\operatorname {LG} (a_{n};x)=\sum _{n=1}^{\infty }a_{n}{\frac {x^{n}}{1-x^{n}}}.$ Note that in a Lambert series the index n starts at 1, not at 0, as the first term would otherwise be undefined.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Formal Dirichlet series are often classified as generating functions, although they are not strictly formal power series.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] If *a**n* is a Dirichlet character then its Dirichlet series generating function is called a Dirichlet L-series.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] We also have a relation between the pair of coefficients in the Lambert series expansions above and their DGFs.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Namely, we can prove that: $[x^{n}]\operatorname {LG} (a_{n};x)=b_{n}$ if and only if $\operatorname {DG} (a_{n};s)\zeta (s)=\operatorname {DG} (b_{n};s),$ where *ζ*(*s*) is the Riemann zeta function.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] The idea of generating functions can be extended to sequences of other objects.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Thus, for example, polynomial sequences of binomial type are generated by: $e^{xf(t)}=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }{\frac {p_{n}(x)}{n!}}t^{n}$ where *p**n*(*x*) is a sequence of polynomials and *f*(*t*) is a function of a certain form.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Sheffer sequences are generated in a similar way.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] See the main article generalized Appell polynomials for more information.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] We see that for non-identically zero convolution families, this definition is equivalent to requiring that the sequence have an ordinary generating function of the first form given above.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Examples of convolution polynomial sequences include the *binomial power series*, 𝓑*t*(*z*) = 1 + *z*𝓑*t*(*z*)*t*, so-termed *tree polynomials*, the Bell numbers, *B*(*n*), the Laguerre polynomials, and the Stirling convolution polynomials.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Polynomials are a special case of ordinary generating functions, corresponding to finite sequences, or equivalently sequences that vanish after a certain point.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] These are important in that many finite sequences can usefully be interpreted as generating functions, such as the Poincaré polynomial and others.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] The left-hand side is the Maclaurin series expansion of the right-hand side.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Alternatively, the equality can be justified by multiplying the power series on the left by 1 − *x*, and checking that the result is the constant power series 1 (in other words, that all coefficients except the one of *x*0 are equal to 0).
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Moreover, there can be no other power series with this property.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] The left-hand side therefore designates the multiplicative inverse of 1 − *x* in the ring of power series.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Expressions for the ordinary generating function of other sequences are easily derived from this one.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] One can also introduce regular gaps in the sequence by replacing x by some power of x, so for instance for the sequence 1, 0, 1, 0, 1, 0, 1, 0, ...
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] so that we can form the analogous generating functions over the integral mth powers generalizing the result in the square case above.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] The ordinary generating function of a sequence can be expressed as a rational function (the ratio of two finite-degree polynomials) if and only if the sequence is a linear recursive sequence with constant coefficients; this generalizes the examples above.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Conversely, every sequence generated by a fraction of polynomials satisfies a linear recurrence with constant coefficients; these coefficients are identical to the coefficients of the fraction denominator polynomial (so they can be directly read off).
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] This observation shows it is easy to solve for generating functions of sequences defined by a linear finite difference equation with constant coefficients, and then hence, for explicit closed-form formulas for the coefficients of these generating functions.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] The prototypical example here is to derive Binet's formula for the Fibonacci numbers via generating function techniques.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] where the reciprocal roots, $\rho _{i}\in \mathbb {C}$ , are fixed scalars and where *p**i*(*n*) is a polynomial in n for all 1 ≤ *i* ≤ *ℓ*.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] In general, Hadamard products of rational functions produce rational generating functions.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] This result is computed in many ways, including Cauchy's integral formula or contour integration, taking complex residues, or by direct manipulations of formal power series in two variables.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Multiplication of ordinary generating functions yields a discrete convolution (the Cauchy product) of the sequences.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] See also the section on convolutions in the applications section of this article below for further examples of problem solving with convolutions of generating functions and interpretations.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] The differentiation–multiplication operation of the second identity can be repeated k times to multiply the sequence by *n**k*, but that requires alternating between differentiation and multiplication.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Related operations of performing fractional integration on a sequence generating function are discussed here.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] In this section we give formulas for generating functions enumerating the sequence {*f**an* + *b*} given an ordinary generating function *F*(*z*), where *a* ≥ 2, 0 ≤ *b* < *a*, and *a* and *b* are integers (see the main article on transformations).
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] More generally, suppose that *a* ≥ 3 and that *ωa* = exp ⁠2*πi*/*a*⁠ denotes the ath primitive root of unity.
