[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] In calculus, often the growth rate of the coefficients of a power series can be used to deduce a radius of convergence for the power series.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] The reverse can also hold; often the radius of convergence for a generating function can be used to deduce the asymptotic growth of the underlying sequence.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Note that limit as n goes to infinity of the ratio of *a**n* to any of these expressions is guaranteed to be 1; not merely that *a**n* is proportional to them.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Often this approach can be iterated to generate several terms in an asymptotic series for *a**n*.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] The asymptotic growth of the coefficients of this generating function can then be sought via the finding of A, B, α, β, and r to describe the generating function, as above.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Similar asymptotic analysis is possible for exponential generating functions; with an exponential generating function, it is ⁠*a**n*/*n*!⁠ that grows according to these asymptotic formulae.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] Generally, if the generating function of one sequence minus the generating function of a second sequence has a radius of convergence that is larger than the radius of convergence of the individual generating functions then the two sequences have the same asymptotic growth.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] The generating function in several variables can be generalized to arrays with multiple indices.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] These non-polynomial double sum examples are called **multivariate generating functions**, or **super generating functions**.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p01] For two variables, these are often called **bivariate generating functions**.
