[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p02] We suggest an approach by generating functions.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p02] In this example, we reformulate a generating function example given in Section 7.3 of *Concrete Mathematics* (see also Section 7.1 of the same reference for pretty pictures of generating function series).
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p02] In particular, suppose that we seek the total number of ways (denoted *Un*) to tile a 3-by-n rectangle with unmarked 2-by-1 domino pieces.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p02] Let the auxiliary sequence, *Vn*, be defined as the number of ways to cover a 3-by-n rectangle-minus-corner section of the full rectangle.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p02] We seek to use these definitions to give a closed form formula for *Un* without breaking down this definition further to handle the cases of vertical versus horizontal dominoes.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p02] A discrete *convolution* of the terms in two formal power series turns a product of generating functions into a generating function enumerating a convolved sum of the original sequence terms (see Cauchy product).
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p02] Multiplication of generating functions, or convolution of their underlying sequences, can correspond to a notion of independent events in certain counting and probability scenarios.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p02] For example, if we adopt the notational convention that the probability generating function, or *pgf*, of a random variable Z is denoted by *GZ*(*z*), then we can show that for any two random variables $G_{X+Y}(z)=G_{X}(z)G_{Y}(z)\,,$ if X and Y are independent.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p02] An example where convolutions of generating functions are useful allows us to solve for a specific closed-form function representing the ordinary generating function for the Catalan numbers, *Cn*.
[src:generating-functions/exponential-generating-function-p02] In particular, this sequence has the combinatorial interpretation as being the number of ways to insert parentheses into the product *x*0 · *x*1 ·⋯· *xn* so that the order of multiplication is completely specified.
