[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] These formal power series over *R* form the **Magnus ring** over *R*.
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] Given an alphabet $\Sigma$ and a semiring S .
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] The formal power series over S supported on the language $\Sigma ^{*}$ is denoted by $S\langle \langle \Sigma ^{*}\rangle \rangle$ .
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] It consists of all mappings $r:\Sigma ^{*}\to S$ , where $\Sigma ^{*}$ is the free monoid generated by the non-empty set $\Sigma$ .
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] where $(r,w)$ denotes the value of r at the word $w\in \Sigma ^{*}$ .
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] The elements $(r,w)\in S$ are called the coefficients of r .
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] A series where every coefficient is either 0 or 1 is called the characteristic series of its support.
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] The subset of $S\langle \langle \Sigma ^{*}\rangle \rangle$ consisting of all series with a finite support is denoted by $S\langle \Sigma ^{*}\rangle$ and called polynomials.
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] With these operations $(S\langle \langle \Sigma ^{*}\rangle \rangle ,+,\cdot ,0,\varepsilon )$ and $(S\langle \Sigma ^{*}\rangle ,+,\cdot ,0,\varepsilon )$ are semirings, where $\varepsilon$ is the empty word in $\Sigma ^{*}$ .
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] These formal power series are used to model the behavior of weighted automata, in theoretical computer science, when the coefficients $(r,w)$ of the series are taken to be the weight of a path with label w in the automata.
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] Suppose G is an ordered abelian group, meaning an abelian group with a total ordering < respecting the group's addition, so that $a<b$ if and only if $a+c<b+c$ for all c .
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] Let **I** be a well-ordered subset of G , meaning **I** contains no infinite descending chain.
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] for all such **I**, with $a_{i}$ in a commutative ring R , where we assume that for any index set, if all of the $a_{i}$ are zero then the sum is zero.
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] Then $R((G))$ is the ring of formal power series on G ; because of the condition that the indexing set be well-ordered the product is well-defined, and we of course assume that two elements which differ by zero are the same.
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] Sometimes the notation $[[R^{G}]]$ is used to denote $R((G))$ .
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] Various properties of R transfer to $R((G))$ .
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] If R is an ordered field, we can order $R((G))$ by setting any element to have the same sign as its leading coefficient, defined as the least element of the index set **I** associated to a non-zero coefficient.
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] Finally if G is a divisible group and R is a real closed field, then $R((G))$ is a real closed field, and if R is algebraically closed, then so is $R((G))$ .
[src:generating-functions/formal-power-series] This theory is due to Hans Hahn, who also showed that one obtains subfields when the number of (non-zero) terms is bounded by some fixed infinite cardinality.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] In number theory and combinatorics, a **partition** of a non-negative integer n, also called an **integer partition**, is a way of writing n as a sum of positive integers.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] Two sums that differ only in the order of their summands are considered the same partition.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] The only partition of zero is the empty sum, having no parts.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] The order-dependent composition 1 + 3 is the same partition as 3 + 1, and the two distinct compositions 1 + 2 + 1 and 1 + 1 + 2 represent the same partition as 2 + 1 + 1.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] An individual summand in a partition is called a **part**.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] The number of partitions of n is given by the partition function *p*(*n*).
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] The notation *λ* ⊢ *n* means that λ is a partition of n.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] Partitions can be graphically visualized with Young diagrams or Ferrers diagrams.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] They occur in a number of branches of mathematics and physics, including the study of symmetric polynomials and of the symmetric group and in group representation theory in general.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] Some authors treat a partition as a non-increasing sequence of summands, rather than an expression with plus signs.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] For example, the partition 2 + 2 + 1 might instead be written as the tuple (2, 2, 1) or in the even more compact form (22, 1) where the superscript indicates the number of repetitions of a part.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] This multiplicity notation for a partition can be written alternatively as $1^{m_{1}}2^{m_{2}}3^{m_{3}}\cdots$ , where *m*1 is the number of 1's, *m*2 is the number of 2's, etc.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] There are two common diagrammatic methods to represent partitions: as Ferrers diagrams, named after Norman Macleod Ferrers, and as Young diagrams, named after Alfred Young.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] Both have several possible conventions; here, we use *English notation*, with diagrams aligned in the upper-left corner.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] The 14 circles are lined up in 4 rows, each having the size of a part of the partition.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] An alternative visual representation of an integer partition is its *Young diagram* (often also called a Ferrers diagram).
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] Rather than representing a partition with dots, as in the Ferrers diagram, the Young diagram uses boxes or squares.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] As a type of shape made by adjacent squares joined together, Young diagrams are a special kind of polyomino.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] The partition function $p(n)$ counts the partitions of a non-negative integer n .
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] No closed-form expression for the partition function is known, but it has both asymptotic expansions that accurately approximate it and recurrence relations by which it can be calculated exactly.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] The multiplicative inverse of its generating function is the Euler function; by Euler's pentagonal number theorem this function is an alternating sum of pentagonal number powers of its argument.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] Srinivasa Ramanujan discovered that the partition function has nontrivial patterns in modular arithmetic, now known as Ramanujan's congruences.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] For instance, whenever the decimal representation of n ends in the digit 4 or 9, the number of partitions of n will be divisible by 5.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] In both combinatorics and number theory, families of partitions subject to various restrictions are often studied.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] This section surveys a few such restrictions.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] By turning the rows into columns, we obtain the partition 4 + 3 + 3 + 2 + 1 + 1 of the number 14.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] Such partitions are said to be *conjugate* of one another.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] In the case of the number 4, partitions 4 and 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 are conjugate pairs, and partitions 3 + 1 and 2 + 1 + 1 are conjugate of each other.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] Of particular interest are partitions, such as 2 + 2, which have themselves as conjugate.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] Such partitions are said to be *self-conjugate*.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] Alternatively, we could count partitions in which no number occurs more than once.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] Such a partition is called a *partition with distinct parts*.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] For each positive number, the number of partitions with odd parts equals the number of partitions with distinct parts, denoted by *q*(*n*).
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] This result was proved by Leonhard Euler in 1748 and later was generalized as Glaisher's theorem.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] For every type of restricted partition there is a corresponding function for the number of partitions satisfying the given restriction.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] An important example is *q*(*n*) (partitions into distinct parts).
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] By taking conjugates, the number *p**k*(*n*) of partitions of *n* into exactly *k* parts is equal to the number of partitions of *n* in which the largest part has size *k*.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] This can be used to solve change-making problems (where the set *T* specifies the available coins).
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] and the number of partitions of *n* in which all parts are 1, 2 or 3 (or, equivalently, the number of partitions of *n* into at most three parts) is the nearest integer to (*n* + 3)2 / 12.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] One may also simultaneously limit the number and size of the parts.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] Let *p*(*N*, *M*; *n*) denote the number of partitions of n with at most M parts, each of size at most N.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] Equivalently, these are the partitions whose Young diagram fits inside an *M* × *N* rectangle.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] There is a recurrence relation $p(N,M;n)=p(N,M-1;n)+p(N-1,M;n-M)$ obtained by observing that $p(N,M;n)-p(N,M-1;n)$ counts the partitions of n into exactly M parts of size at most N, and subtracting 1 from each part of such a partition yields a partition of *n* − *M* into at most M parts.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] The *rank* of a partition is the largest number *k* such that the partition contains at least *k* parts of size at least *k*.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] For example, the partition 4 + 3 + 3 + 2 + 1 + 1 has rank 3 because it contains 3 parts that are ≥ 3, but does not contain 4 parts that are ≥ 4.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] The Durfee square has applications within combinatorics in the proofs of various partition identities.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] It also has some practical significance in the form of the h-index.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] A different statistic is also sometimes called the rank of a partition (or Dyson rank), namely, the difference $\lambda _{k}-k$ for a partition of *k* parts with largest part $\lambda _{k}$ .
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] This statistic (which is unrelated to the one described above) appears in the study of Ramanujan congruences.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] There is a natural partial order on partitions given by inclusion of Young diagrams.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] This partially ordered set is known as *Young's lattice*.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] The lattice was originally defined in the context of representation theory, where it is used to describe the irreducible representations of symmetric groups *S**n* for all *n*, together with their branching properties, in characteristic zero.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] It also has received significant study for its purely combinatorial properties; notably, it is the motivating example of a differential poset.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] There is a deep theory of random partitions chosen according to the uniform probability distribution on the symmetric group via the Robinson–Schensted correspondence.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] In 1977, Logan and Shepp, as well as Vershik and Kerov, showed that the Young diagram of a typical large partition becomes asymptotically close to the graph of a certain analytic function minimizing a certain functional.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] In 1988, Baik, Deift and Johansson extended these results to determine the distribution of the longest increasing subsequence of a random permutation in terms of the Tracy–Widom distribution.
[src:generating-functions/partition-number-theory] Okounkov related these results to the combinatorics of Riemann surfaces and representation theory.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] In mathematics, particularly in combinatorics, a **Stirling number of the second kind** (or **Stirling partition number**) is the number of ways to partition a set of *n* objects into *k* non-empty subsets and is denoted by $S(n,k)$ or $\textstyle \left\{{n \atop k}\right\}$ .
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] Stirling numbers of the second kind occur in combinatorics and the study of partitions.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] The Stirling numbers of the first and second kind can be understood as inverses of one another when viewed as triangular matrices.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] This article is devoted to specifics of Stirling numbers of the second kind.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] Identities linking the two kinds appear in the article on Stirling numbers.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] The Stirling numbers of the second kind, written $S(n,k)$ or $\lbrace \textstyle {n \atop k}\rbrace$ or with other notations, count the number of ways to partition a set of n labelled objects into k nonempty unlabelled subsets.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] Equivalently, they count the number of different equivalence relations with precisely k equivalence classes that can be defined on an n element set.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] In fact, there is a bijection between the set of partitions and the set of equivalence relations on a given set.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] as there is no empty partition of a nonempty set, the only way to partition an *n*-element set into *n* parts is to put each element of the set into its own part, and the only way to partition a nonempty set into one part is to put all of the elements in the same part.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] Various notations have been used for Stirling numbers of the second kind.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] The brace notation ${\textstyle \textstyle \lbrace {n \atop k}\rbrace }$ was used by Imanuel Marx and Antonio Salmeri in 1962 for variants of these numbers.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] This led Knuth to use it, as shown here, in the first volume of *The Art of Computer Programming* (1968).
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] According to the third edition of *The Art of Computer Programming*, this notation was also used earlier by Jovan Karamata in 1935.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] The notation *S*(*n*, *k*) was used by Richard Stanley in his book *Enumerative Combinatorics* and also, much earlier, by many other writers.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] The notations used on this page for Stirling numbers are not universal, and may conflict with notations in other sources.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] over all values of *k* is the total number of partitions of a set with *n* members.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] This number is known as the *n*th Bell number.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] As with the binomial coefficients, this table could be extended to *k* > *n*, but the entries would all be 0.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] For instance, the number 25 in column *k* = 3 and row *n* = 5 is given by 25 = 7 + (3×6), where 7 is the number above and to the left of 25, 6 is the number above 25 and 3 is the column containing the 6.
