[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] If you swap $(j-2)!$ from the first sum and $(-1)^{j}$ from the second, you will get similar conjectures, but for Stirling numbers of the first kind.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] This is because dividing *n* elements into *n* − 1 sets necessarily means dividing it into one set of size 2 and *n* − 2 sets of size 1.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] To see this, first note that there are 2*n* *ordered* pairs of complementary subsets *A* and *B*.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] In one case, *A* is empty, and in another *B* is empty, so 2*n* − 2 ordered pairs of subsets remain.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] Finally, since we want *unordered* pairs rather than *ordered* pairs we divide this last number by 2, giving the result above.
