[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] For fixed n , $\left\{{n \atop k}\right\}$ is unimodal, that is, the sequence increases and then decreases.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] The maximum is attained for at most two consecutive values of *k*.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] In particular, the *n*th moment of the Poisson distribution with expected value 1 is precisely the number of partitions of a set of size *n*, i.e., it is the *n*th Bell number (this fact is Dobiński's formula).
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] Let the random variable *X* be the number of fixed points of a uniformly distributed random permutation of a finite set of size *m*.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] In other words, the *n*th moment of this probability distribution is the number of partitions of a set of size *n* into no more than *m* parts.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] This is proved in the article on random permutation statistics, although the notation is a bit different.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] The Stirling numbers of the second kind can represent the total number of rhyme schemes for a poem of *n* lines. $S(n,k)$ gives the number of possible rhyming schemes for *n* lines using *k* unique rhyming syllables.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] As an example, for a poem of 3 lines, there is 1 rhyme scheme using just one rhyme (aaa), 3 rhyme schemes using two rhymes (aab, aba, abb), and 1 rhyme scheme using three rhymes (abc).
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] The *r*-Stirling number of the second kind $\left\{{n \atop k}\right\}_{r}$ counts the number of partitions of a set of *n* objects into *k* non-empty disjoint subsets, such that the first *r* elements are in distinct subsets.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] An *r*-associated Stirling number of the second kind is the number of ways to partition a set of *n* objects into *k* subsets, with each subset containing at least *r* elements.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] The 2-associated numbers (sequence A008299 in the OEIS) appear elsewhere as "Ward numbers" and as the magnitudes of the coefficients of Mahler polynomials.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] Denote the *n* objects to partition by the integers 1, 2, ..., *n*.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] Define the reduced Stirling numbers of the second kind, denoted $S^{d}(n,k)$ , to be the number of ways to partition the integers 1, 2, ..., *n* into *k* nonempty subsets such that all elements in each subset have pairwise distance at least *d*.
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] That is, for any integers *i* and *j* in a given subset, it is required that $|i-j|\geq d$ .
[src:generating-functions/stirling-numbers-of-the-second-kind] Observe (both by definition and by the reduction formula), that $S^{1}(n,k)=S(n,k)$ , the familiar Stirling numbers of the second kind.
